    description: 'The gradual loosening of censorship in the Soviet Union resulted in a "perestroika wave" in Soviet literature. The country\'s readers took pleasure not only in the works by young authors, but also in the new books by well-known writers. In 1985, Valentin Rasputin\'s "Fire" was a real literary eye-opener; in 1986, Chingiz Aitmatov\'s "The Scaffold" was an event of similar magnitude, as, in 1987, was Viktor Astafyev\'s "The Sad Detective." The best sellers of the perestroika years were in vastly different genres, from profound fables to high-quality realistic novels, but what they all had in common was their hard-edged discussion of the flaws of the Soviet system. Especially vociferous in their criticism were the works by Vladimir Dudintsev ("The White Robes"), Yury Dombrovsky ("The Faculty of Useless Knowledge"), and Danil Granin ("The Bison"). \n \n A notable example of the lifting of all former restrictions was the publication of Venedikt Yerofeyev\'s prose poem "Moscow to the End of the Line." In the 1988 edition of this work, all the expletives of the original text were replaced with three dots. Some time later, this poem appeared in its intended form. In the late 1980s, the journals and literary almanacs began to publish outrageous stories by another representative of contemporary Russian postmodernism, Vladimir Sorokin. And until 1988, no works by Victor Erofeyev, who had been expelled from the Writers\' Union of the USSR, had been published in the Soviet Union. Erofeyev\'s novel "Russian Beauty," published in 1990, was translated into more than twenty languages and became an international bestseller. \n \n Overwhelmed by the avalanche of such unprecedented literary riches, readers were buying books and journals with a vengeance, which resulted in a shortage of paper. Millions of Soviet citizens were not sure if the transformations were there to stay, so they tried hard to make up for the time lost during the decades of ruthless ideological and aesthetic censorship.',
